Rustenburg Community activist Napoleon Webster, charged with escape from lawful custody, appeared alongside six others men in the Bafokeng Magistrate's Court in Tlhabane on Monday. Their case was rolled over to Tuesday, for bail application. The defence applied for a postponement stating that some of the accused were appearing on another matter in court on Tuesday. The other six are facing charges of aiding and abetting a suspect to escape and defeating the ends of justice. The case stems from an incident on January 6, at the Bafokeng Magistrate's Court in Tlhabane near Rustenburg, where Webster was arrested on a murder charge while attending court proceeding involving a case in which a man was killed at Marikana West in December.&nbsp;Webster was handcuffed and put inside a police vehicle (sedan) that was parked near the court entrance. North West police said after he was put in a police vehicle, a group of men armed with assortment of dangerous weapons including assegais, spears, stones and pangas allegedly advanced towards the police vehicle and attempted to release him. The police had to fire warning shots of which the men ignored and in the process managed to free Webster, got inside a Mercedes Benz Sprinter and fled the scene. The police, including those who were at court to secure the proceedings where the escapee s accomplice was appearing, gave chase. The suspects abandoned their vehicle at Mokwena Street in Tlhabane due to a flat tyre. They were arrested together with Webster, who was still handcuffed. African News Agency